## 3. Agent Processing Flow

### Step 1: Policy Validation
- JSON schema validation
- Rule conflict detection
- Priority ordering
- Resource availability check

### Step 2: eBPF Map Translation
```bash
# Agent converts policy to eBPF map operations
# IP 8.8.8.8 = 0x08080808 in network byte order
# Protocol ICMP = 1
bpftool map update id 8 key hex 08080808 value hex 01
```

### Step 3: Kernel Enforcement
- eBPF program reads from maps in real-time
- Packet inspection at kernel level
- Drop/allow decisions based on map data
- Statistics collection

## 4. eBPF Infrastructure

### BPF Maps Used

#### Policy Storage Map
```c
struct {
    __uint(type, BPF_MAP_TYPE_HASH);
    __uint(max_entries, 4096);
    __type(key, __u32);     // IP address (network byte order)
    __type(value, __u8);    // Protocol (1=ICMP, 6=TCP, 17=UDP, 255=ALL)
} aegis_blocked_destinations;
```

#### Statistics Map
```c
struct {
    __uint(type, BPF_MAP_TYPE_PERCPU_ARRAY);
    __uint(max_entries, 20);
    __type(key, __u32);     // Stat type
    __type(value, __u64);   // Counter value
} aegis_enforcement_stats;
```

### eBPF Program Logic
```c
SEC("classifier")
int aegis_enforce(struct __sk_buff *skb)
{
    // Extract IP and protocol from packet
    __u32 dest_ip = get_dest_ip(skb);
    __u8 protocol = get_protocol(skb);
    
    // Check policy map
    __u8 *blocked = bpf_map_lookup_elem(&aegis_blocked_destinations, &dest_ip);
    if (blocked && (*blocked == protocol || *blocked == 255)) {
        update_stats(STAT_PACKETS_BLOCKED);
        return TC_ACT_SHOT;  // Drop packet
    }
    
    return TC_ACT_OK;  // Allow packet
}
```

